{"title_page": "Ruhollah Khomeini's life in exile", "text_new": "[[File:Portrait of Ruhollah Khomeini.jpg|150 px|thumb|right|Khomeini, leader of Iranian revolution]]\n\n'''Ruhollah Khomeini's life in exile''' was the period that [[Grand Ayatollah]] [[Ruhollah Khomeini]] spent from 1964 to 1979 in [[Turkey]], [[Iraq]] and [[France]], after Mohamed Reza Shah Pahlavi had arrested him twice for dissent from his \u201c[[White Revolution]]\u201d announced in 1963. [[Ruhollah Khomeini|Ayatollah Khomeini]] was invited back to Iran by the government,<ref name=\"Milani Shah\">{{cite book|last=Milani|first=Abbas|title=The Shah|url=https://books.google.com/?id=3e2L0Nt6NgQC&printsec=frontcover&dq=The+Shah#v=onepage&q=The%20Shah&f=false|isbn=9780230340381|date=22 May 2012}}</ref><ref name=Milani-Persians>{{cite book|last=Milani|first=Abbas|title=Eminent Persians|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ixU33FaG_dgC|isbn=978-0-8156-0907-0|publisher=Syracuse University Press|year=2008}}</ref>and returned to [[Tehran]] from exile on 1979.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/february/1/newsid_2521000/2521003.stm 1979: Exiled Ayatollah Khomeini returns to Iran] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141024113747/http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/february/1/newsid_2521000/2521003.stm |date=24 October 2014 }}| bbc.co.uk</ref>\n\nOn 4 November 1964, Khomeini was secretly taken to [[Ankara]] and then to [[Bursa]], [[Turkey]]. On 5 September 1965, he moved to [[Najaf]], [[Iraq]] and stayed there until Saddam Hussein deported him. Finally, he was exiled by the pressure of [[Mohammad Reza Pahlavi]] to [[Neauphle-le-Ch\u00e2teau]], [[Paris]] on 6 October 1978.<ref name=\"Islam\">{{cite book |last1=Mutalib |first1=Hussin |title=Islam, Muslims and the Modern State: Case-Studies of Muslims in Thirteen Countries |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan (June 18, 1996) |isbn=978-0-333-66969-3}}</ref>\n\n==Political activity before exile==\n[[File:\u062e\u0645\u06cc\u0646\u06cc \u0648 \u0645\u0631\u062f\u0645.JPG|200 px|thumb|right|Khomeini with people]]\nIn 1944 Khomeini published his first book, ''[[Kashf al-Asrar]]'' (\u201cSecrets Unveiled\u201d), attacking secularisation under [[Reza Shah Pahlavi]] and advocating for the power of [[Allah]] to establish and disestablish governments.<ref>Vahdat, Farzin; ''God and Juggernaut: Iran's Intellectual Encounter With Modernity'', p. 182 {{ISBN|9780815629474}}</ref>\nAfter the death of Borujerdi in 1961, Khomeini became the leading ''Marja'''.<ref name=\"q\">{{cite book |last1=Fadaee |first1=Simin |title=Social Movements in Iran: Environmentalism and Civil Society (Iranian Studies) |publisher=Routledge; 1 edition (March 29, 2012) |isbn=978-0-415-69357-8 |page=55 |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Social_Movements_in_Iran.html?id=jsKKYuNky_0C}}</ref> \n\nIn January 1963, the Shah announced the [[White Revolution]], a six-point program of reform calling for land reform, nationalization of the forests, the sale of state-owned enterprises to private interests, electoral changes to enfranchise women and allow non-Muslims to hold office, profit-sharing in industry, and a literacy campaign in the nation's schools. On the other hand, he and many religious leaders considered the revolution had trends of westernizing the country and would in their mind threaten the traditional Islamic lifestyle of the common folk.<ref>[http://www.nmhschool.org/tthornton/mehistorydatabase/arabisraeliwars.htm#white%20revolution] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071224172550/http://www.nmhschool.org/tthornton/mehistorydatabase/arabisraeliwars.htm#white%20revolution |date=24 December 2007 }}</ref>\nThe Shah himself traveled to Qom and announced the clergy black reactionaries worse than the red reactionaries and a hundred times more treacherous than the (communist) tudeh party during his speech. On 26th January 1963, he held a referendum to get the appearance of public support in which 5.6 million against 4.1 people vote for the reformation. The referendum was a good excuse for the government to take tougher practical action against the clergy and on 22nd march 1963, coincides with the death-day of [[Ja'far al-Sadiq]], the Shah's guards attacked [[Feyziyeh School]]and kill students and people. <ref>{{cite book |last1=Singh;  Singh |first1=Manjit , D.P. |title=Violence: Impact and Intervention |publisher=Atlantic (2008) |isbn=978-8126909414 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=38SwtIHR11QC&pg=PA79&lpg=PA79&dq=SAVAK+attack+on+Feyziyeh+1963&source=bl&ots=SzVaSGZr6e&sig=ACfU3U3rVn4mdd-TKN0J02TBudnh9tua0w&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjNw47UzeHkAhXMJFAKHXPrA2kQ6AEwGXoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=SAVAK%20attack%20on%20Feyziyeh%201963&f=false}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Koya |first1=Abdar Rahman |title=Imam Khomeini: Life, Thought and Legacy |publisher=Islamic Book Trust (June 1, 2010) |isbn=978-9675062254 |page=32 |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Imam_Khomeini_Life_Thought_and_Legacy.html?id=HMd5C4KaOgkC}}</ref>According to Daniel Brumberg, the regime persuaded the thugs to attack the students of Feyziyeh School.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Brumberg |first1=Daniel |title=Reinventing Khomeini The Struggle for Reform in Iran |publisher=University Of Chicago Press (April 15, 2001) |isbn=978-0226077574 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aPT9QRtDMr8C&pg=PA74&lpg=PA74&dq=attack+to+feyziye#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> On the afternoon of [[Ashura]] (3 June 1963),  Khomeini presented a lecture at the Feyziyeh School<ref>{{cite book |last1=Sharifi Isaloo |first1=Amin |title=Power, Legitimacy and the Public Sphere: The Iranian Taziyeh Theatre Ritual |publisher=Taylor & Francis Group, 2018 |isbn=978-0-367-08541-4 |page=85 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LzbvugEACAAJ&dq=Power,+Legitimacy+and+the+Public+Sphere&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjXmZv5nNjdAhWGBiwKHZhmDeEQ6AEILDAB}}</ref> and inculpated the Shah as a \"wretched miserable man\", advised him to change his  ways, otherwise the day will come that people will be happy to see him leave, drawing parallels to the caliph Yazid, who is perceived as a 'tyrant' by [[Shia Islam|Shias]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iranchamber.com/history/rkhomeini/ayatollah_khomeini.php |title= Moin, Khomeini |year= 2000 |page= 104}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Nineteen Years on Departure of Islamic Republic Founder |url=https://www.english.alahednews.com.lb/essaydetails.php?eid=3948&cid=391#.W6yOdHszaM9}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 June 1963 at 3 am, two days after, Khomeini was detained and transferred to [[Tehran]]. When this news was broadcast, large protest demonstrations were held in Qom, Tehran, [[Mashhad]], [[Varamin]], [[Kashan]] and other cities. The Shah's guards killed and injured several people. That event is now referred to as the [[Movement of 15 Khordad]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hiro |first1=Dilip |title=Iran Under the Ayatollahs (Routledge Revivals) |publisher=Routledge; 1 edition (February 16, 2013) |isbn=978-0-415-66969-6 |page=47}}</ref> On 3 August, the Shah released Khomeini from jail and placed him under house arrest.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hiro |first1=Dilip |title=Iran Under the Ayatollahs (Routledge Revivals) |publisher=Routledge; 1 edition (February 16, 2013) |isbn=978-0-415-66969-6 |page=48|url=https://www.amazon.com/Iran-Under-Ayatollahs-Routledge-Revivals/dp/0415669693}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 October 1964, Khomeini condemned the Shah because of the [[diplomatic immunity]] he granted to [[American citizens]], civilian or military personnel in Iran.<ref name=\"q\" /> On 4 November 1964 Khomeini was arrested by [[SAVAK]]. He was then taken to Mehrabad international airport in Tehran and sent to Turkey.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hiro |first1=Dilip |title=Iran Under the Ayatollahs (Routledge Revivals) |publisher=Routledge; 1 edition (February 16, 2013) |isbn=978-0-415-66969-6 |page=49 |url=https://www.amazon.com/Iran-Under-Ayatollahs-Routledge-Revivals/dp/0415669693}}</ref>\n\n== Life in exile ==\n[[File:\u062e\u0645\u06cc\u0646\u06cc \u062f\u0631 \u062a\u0631\u06a9\u06cc\u0647.JPG|150 px|thumb|Khomeini in exile at [[Bursa]], Turkey without clerical dress]]\n\n=== Turkey ===\nA week after his arrival in Turkey, Khomeini was sent to [[Bursa]] and he stayed there for eleven months. He was hosted by a colonel in the Turkish Military intelligence named Ali Cetiner in his own residence.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sciolino |first=Elaine |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9E06E0D9153EF934A1575BC0A9669C8B63&sec=&pagewanted=all |title=nyt.com The People's Shah |work=The New York Times |date=27 August 2000 |accessdate=19 March 2010}}</ref> According to Turkish law, clerical dress was banned and Khomeini was never allowed to meet people. On 3 December 1964, his son, [[Mostafa Khomeini|Mostafa]], joined him.<ref name=\"w\">{{cite web |last1=Algar |first1=Dr. Hamid |title=Imam Khomeini: A Short Biography |url=https://www.al-islam.org/imam-khomeini-short-biography-dr-hamid-algar/years-struggle-and-exile-1962-1978 |publisher=The Institute for the Compilation and Publication of the Works of Imam Khomeini}}</ref> In his first days in Turkey, Khomeini was extremely angry at the secular dress of Turkish women, but he learned to adapt quickly to his new surroundings.<ref>Willett, Edward; ''Ayatollah Khomeini'', p. 48 {{ISBN|0823944654}}</ref> Despite the bans on contact with Khomeini, he and his students \u2013 most notably future [[President of Iran|President]] [[Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani]] \u2013 would plot the successful assassination of [[Prime Minister of Iran|Prime Minister]] [[Hassan-Ali Mansur]] as soon as Khomeini left Iran.<ref name=\"Evolution\"/>\n\nIn Bursa, Khomeini possessed a great deal of spare time, with the result that he continued his studies and for the first time moved away from the \u201ctraditional\u201d view of clerical involvement in politics.<ref>Rahimi, Babak; ''Contentious Legacies of the Ayatollah'', in Adib-Moghaddam, Arshin (editor); ''A Critical Introduction to Khomeini'', p. 296 {{ISBN|1107012678}}</ref> He wrote his second book, ''[[Tahrir al-Wasilah]]'', and began to receive huge donations from Iranian supporters who already opposed the Shah\u2019s policies.<ref name=\"Khomeini135137\">{{cite book |last1=Moin |first1=Baqer |title=Khomeini: Life of the Ayatollah |publisher=I.B. Tauris; Reprint edition (July 15, 2009) |isbn=978-1-84511-790-0 |pages=135-137}}</ref> The extent of donations to the Ayatollah caused the Shah and Turkish government to lift the ban on communication with his during the summer of 1965, and several clergy visited Khomeini \u2013 who was wearing secular garb \u2013 in Istanbul in 1965.<ref name=\"Khomeini135137\"/>\n\nOn September 5, 1965, Khomeini left Turkey and went to Najaf in Iraq.<ref name=\"e\">{{cite book |last1=Koya |first1=Abdar Rahman |title=Iman Khomeini: Life, Thought and Legacy |publisher=Islamic Book Trust (June 1, 2010) |isbn=978-9675062254 |page=36}}</ref>\n\nThe reasons for Khomeini's exile to Najaf by the Shah's regime are described as:<ref name=\"w\" />\n# The regime hoped to diminish the role of Khomeini through competition with Iraqi Ulama like [[Abu al-Qasim al-Khoei]]<ref>{{cite book |last1=Moin |first1=Baqer |title=Khomeini: Life of the Ayatollah |publisher=I.B. Tauris; Reprint edition (July 15, 2009) |isbn=978-1-84511-790-0 |pages=141}}</ref>\n# Because of intense pressure and popular protests.\n# Scholars and Khomeini's followers began to communicate with him in Bursa, donating so much money that the Ayatollah went from virtually penniless to very rich\n#  A [[SAVAK]] agent thought that his presence made the Turkish people hostile toward the Shah\u2019s regime.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Moin |first1=Baqer |title=Khomeini: Life of the Ayatollah |publisher=I.B. Tauris; Reprint edition (July 15, 2009) |isbn=978-1-84511-790-0 |page=138}}</ref>\n\n=== Iraq ===\n[[File:Rouhollah Khomeini in exile, Najaf, Pilgrimage the shrine of Imam Ali (3).jpg|150 px|thumb|Rouhollah Khomeini in exile, Najaf, Pilgrimage the shrine of Imam Ali]]\nOn 8 September 1965, Khomeini entered Iraq<ref name=\"e\" /> and would spend thirteen years there. Iraq did not have good political relations with the Shah.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Woods |first1=Kevin M. |title=Saddam's Generals: Perspectives of the Iran-Iraq War |publisher=Institute for Defense Analysis; 1st edition (October 28, 2011) |isbn=978-0-16-089613-2 |page=89 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=A6k9EFp_ijEC&q=Saddam%E2%80%99s+Generals:+Perspectives+of+the+Iran-Iraq+War&dq=Saddam%E2%80%99s+Generals:+Perspectives+of+the+Iran-Iraq+War&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjayYbxiuLdAhUpPewKHZu2DBEQ6AEIJjAA}}</ref>\n\nKhomeini and Mostafa entered Iraq. He went to [[Kadhimiya]] and stayed in the company of [[Mohammad al-Husayni al-Shirazi]] for two days before going to [[Karbala]]. From there he went to the city of Najaf.<ref name=\"r\">{{cite web |last1=Al-Awsat |first1=Asharq |title=Khomeini: From Ataturk Avenue to the Holy City of Najaf |url=https://eng-archive.aawsat.com/theaawsat/features/khomeini-from-ataturk-avenue-to-the-holy-city-of-najaf}}</ref> Initially, Khomeini was isolated by Iraq\u2019s Shi'a clergy because of his status as a foreigner and his radical teachings and support for [[Islamic terrorism|terrorism]]<ref name=\"Evolution\">Zahed, Mosa; ''The Evolution and Ascension of Iran\u2019s Terror Apparatus'', in Casaca, Paulo and Wolf, Siegfried O. (editors); ''Terrorism Revisited: Islamism, Political Violence and State-Sponsorship'', p. 67 {{ISBN|9783319556895}}</ref>; however, after a while [[ Muhammad Baqir al-Sadr ]] and other Iraqi clerics would join with Khomeini because they shared similar aims in establishing an Islamic state.<ref name=\"Evolution\"/> Khomeini would also be helped in his first days in Iraq by then-President [[Abdul Salam Arif]], who allowed the Ayatollah to set up and control an Iranian opposition radio station.<ref name=\"Evolution\"/>\n\nAfter a while, his wife [[Khadijeh Saqafi]] and second son [[Ahmad Khomeini]] joined them in Najaf.<ref name=\"r\" /> Khomeini began teaching [[Fiqh]] in the Sheikh Morteza Ansari Madrassah which captivated students mainly from Iran, Iraq, India, Pakistan, Afghanistan, and the Persian Gulf states.<ref name=\"y\">{{cite book |last1=Koya |first1=Abdar Rahman |title=Imam Khomeini: Life, Thought and Legacy |publisher=Islamic Book Trust (June 1, 2010) |isbn=978-9675062254 |page=37 |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Imam_Khomeini_Life_Thought_and_Legacy.html?id=HMd5C4KaOgkC}}</ref> On April 1967, Khomeini wrote the two letters, once to Ulama in order to persuade them to attempt to overthrow the Shah's regime and another to [[Amir-Abbas Hoveyda]], protesting the coronation of the Shah<ref>Dabashi, Hamid; ''Theology of Discontent: The Ideological Foundation of the Islamic Revolution'', p. ''lix'' {{ISBN|1412805163}}</ref> and condemning him for continued violation of both Islam and [[Persian Constitution of 1906|the constitution]].<ref>Algar, Hamid; ''Roots of the Islamic Revolution in Iran'', {{ISBN|9780905081168}}</ref> Also, Khomeini forbade any type of dealing with Israel.<ref name=\"i\">{{cite book |last1=Koya |first1=Abdar Rahman |title=Imam Khomeini: Life, Thought and Legacy |publisher=Islamic Book Trust (June 1, 2010) |isbn=978-9675062254 |page=38}}</ref> Four years into his Iraqi exile, between 21 January and 8 February (1970), Khomeini gave lectures about [[Guardianship of the Islamic Jurist|Vilayat-e Faq\u012bh]] ya [[Islamic state|Hukumat-i Islami]], which in Shia Islam hold that Islam gives a ''faq\u012bh'' (Islamic jurist) custodianship over people.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">''[[Islam and Revolution]]'' (1981), pp. 29\u201330.</ref>\n\nThis became Khomeini\u2019s most famous and influential work, and laid out his ideas on governance (at that time):\n\n* That the laws of society should be made up only of the laws of God (''[[Sharia]]''), which cover \"all human affairs\" and \"provide instruction and establish norms\" for every \"topic\" in \"human life.\"<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n* Since ''Shariah'', or Islamic law, is the proper law, those holding government posts should have knowledge of ''Sharia.'' Since Islamic jurists or ''faq\u012bh'' have studied and are the most knowledgeable in ''Sharia'', the country's ruler should be a ''[[faq\u012bh]]'' who \"surpasses all others in knowledge\" of Islamic law and justice,<ref>''Islam and Revolution'' (1981), p. 59.</ref> (known as a [[Marja al-taqlid|marja']]), as well as having intelligence and administrative ability. Rule by monarchs and/or assemblies of \"those claiming to be representatives of the majority of the people\" (i.e. elected parliaments and legislatures) has been proclaimed \"wrong\" by Islam.<ref>''Islam and Revolution'', (1981), p. 31, 56</ref>\n* This system of clerical rule is necessary to prevent injustice, corruption, oppression by the powerful over the poor and weak, innovation and deviation of Islam and Sharia law; and also to destroy anti-Islamic influence and conspiracies by non-Muslim foreign powers.<ref>''Islam and Revolution'' (1981), p. 54.</ref> The theory in Shia Islam which holds that Islam gives a ''faq\u012bh'' (Islamic jurist) custodianship over people.\n\nTo formed an Islamic government, Two things were needed:<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hovsepian-Bearce |first1=Yvette Hovsepian-Bearce |title=The Political Ideology of Ayatollah Khamenei: Out of the Mouth of the Supreme Leader of Iran (UCLA Center for Middle East Development (CMED) series) |publisher=Routledge; 1 edition (May 20, 2017) |isbn=978-1-138-08655-5 |page=9}}</ref>\n# Overthrow of the Shah\n# Establishment of Shi'i theocracy\nKhomeini had mooted this theory as early as the middle 1940s in his first book ''Kashf al-Asrar''.<ref name=\"y\" />\n\nFrom 1971 to 1975, Khomeini demonstrated vehement opposition to the [[2,500 year celebration of the Persian Empire]], and the changing of the Iranian calendar from [[Islamic calendar|Hijri]] to Imperial (Shahanshahi).<ref name=\"i\" /> During this era, the Shah considered exiling Khomeini, now known as the \u201cImam\u201d, to [[India]], because he believed doing so would make communication between the Imam and his followers in Iran impossible,<ref name=\"i\" /> but for an unrevealed reason this plan was never executed. Khomeini was also faced with hostility from the [[Ba'athist Iraq|Ba'ath regime]], which began so hostile to his brand of Islam as the Shah.<ref>Bernhardt, Florian; \u2018Firm conviction or forced belief? The Islamic Da\u2018wah Party\u2019s response to Khomeini\u2019s theory of ''wilayat al-faqih''\u2019; ''International Journal of Contemporary Iraqi Studies'', Volume 6, Number 3, 1 September 2012, pp. 299-314</ref>\n\nIn November 1977, the Shah's overthrow began with the assassination of Khomeini's son, Mostafa, by SAVAK.<ref name=\"i\" /><ref name=\"y\" />\n\n[[File:Ruhollah Khomeini in Neauphle-le-Ch\u00e2teau (37).jpg|200 px|thumb|right|Imam Khomeini, in Neauphle-le-Ch\u00e2teau, Paris, France]]\n\n=== France ===\nOn September 24, 1978, according to a meeting held in [[New York City]] between Iraqi and Iranian foreign minister,<ref>Campo, Juan Eduardo; ''Encyclopedia of Islam'', p. 436 {{ISBN|0816077452}}</ref> Khomeini was forced by Iraqi strongman [[Saddam Hussein]] to leave Najaf, although the Shah and Hussein had begun plans to expel the Imam as early as 1975.<ref>Law, Diane; ''The Secret History of the Great Dictators: Saddam Hussein'' {{ISBN|1780333382}}</ref> The Ayatollah preferred to go to another Muslim country, and obtained [[travel visa|a visa]] for [[visa policy of Kuwait|Kuwait]],<ref name=\"Religious\">Mohammad Ayatollahi Tabaar; ''Religious Statecraft: The Politics of Islam in Iran'', p. 65 {{ISBN|0231183666}}</ref> but was turned back at the border because he had obtained the visa under the name \u201cRuhollah Mustafavi\u201d.<ref>Rajaee, Farhang; ''Islamism and Modernism: The Changing Discourse in Iran'', p. 113 {{ISBN|0292774362}}</ref> Khomeini\u2019s next preference was to go to [[Syria]] \u2013 where some sources say the Imam had intended to permanently reside even when he attempted to enter [[Kuwait]]<ref>Buchan James; ''Days of God: The Revolution in Iran and Its Consequences'', p. 177 {{ISBN|1416597778}}</ref> \u2013 but the lingering influence of [[Ahmed Hassan al-Bakr]] in Iraqi and Syrian politics meant that [[Syrian government]] would not accept him.<ref>Ganji, Babak; ''Politics of Confrontation: The Foreign Policy of the USA and Revolutionary Iran'', p. 39</ref> Khomeini then considered going to [[Bahrain]], [[India]], [[Pakistan]] or [[Algeria]],<ref name=\"Religious\"/> but his US-educated nationalist aide, [[Ebrahim Yazdi]], argued that Khomeini should move to the West because of the greater communication opportunities offered there, with Paris offering the best option for communication with the world of his revolutionary message.<ref> Mohammad Ayatollahi Tabaar; ''Religious Statecraft''. p. 66</ref>\n\nOn October 11, 1978, after Khomeini was moved to [[Neauphle-le-Ch\u00e2teau]] outside [[Paris]], France. From the advantages this decision was to keep faraway clerics and Ulama.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Chehabi |first1=H.E. |title=Iranian Politics and Religious Modernism: The Liberation Movement of Iran Under the Shah and Khomeini |publisher=Cornell University Press; 1 edition (January 1, 1990) |isbn=978-0-8014-2416-8 |page=242 |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Iranian_Politics_and_Religious_Modernism.html?id=JJEIQbUnGyYC}}</ref> Citiation in Frances such as some communication facilities and political atmosphere make more efficient relation with people in Iran. In France, because of journalists and the press, Khomeini's speeches were published rapidly in global media.<ref name=\"y\" /> Khomeini wanted to people that continued protests against the government.<ref>Moin, ''Khomeini'', (2000), p. 203</ref>  Between August and December 1978, strikes and demonstrations paralyzed Iran, so that the Shah left the country for exile on 16 January 1979, as the last Persian monarch, leaving his duties to a regency council and an opposition-based prime minister, [[Shapour Bakhtiar]].\n==Return from exile==\nOn Thursday, 1 February 1979, Ruhollah Khomeini was invited back to Iran by the government<ref name=\"Milani-Persians\"/><ref name=\"Milani Shah\"/> and returned to Iran.<ref name=\"i\" />\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Ideocracy]]\n* [[Ruhollah Khomeini]]\n* [[Ruhollah Khomeini's letter to Mikhail Gorbachev]]\n* [[Ruhollah Khomeini's residency (Jamaran)]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Iran|Politics|Shia Islam}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Khomeini, Ruhollah}}\n[[Category:Ruhollah Khomeini| ]]\n[[Category:Iranian emigrants to France]]\n[[Category:Iranian emigrants to Iraq]]\n[[Category:Iranian emigrants to Turkey]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Portrait of Ruhollah Khomeini.jpg|150 px|thumb|right|Khomeini, leader of Iranian revolution]]\n\n'''Ruhollah Khomeini's life in exile''' was the period that [[Grand Ayatollah]] [[Ruhollah Khomeini]] spent from 1964 to 1979 in [[Turkey]], [[Iraq]] and [[France]], after Mohamed Reza Shah Pahlavi had arrested him twice for dissent from his \u201c[[White Revolution]]\u201d announced in 1963. [[Ruhollah Khomeini|Ayatollah Khomeini]] was invited back to Iran by the government,<ref name=\"Milani Shah\">{{cite book|last=Milani|first=Abbas|title=The Shah|url=https://books.google.com/?id=3e2L0Nt6NgQC&printsec=frontcover&dq=The+Shah#v=onepage&q=The%20Shah&f=false|isbn=9780230340381|date=22 May 2012}}</ref><ref name=Milani-Persians>{{cite book|last=Milani|first=Abbas|title=Eminent Persians|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ixU33FaG_dgC|isbn=978-0-8156-0907-0|publisher=Syracuse University Press|year=2008}}</ref>and returned to [[Tehran]] from exile on 1979.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/february/1/newsid_2521000/2521003.stm 1979: Exiled Ayatollah Khomeini returns to Iran] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141024113747/http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/february/1/newsid_2521000/2521003.stm |date=24 October 2014 }}| bbc.co.uk</ref>\n\nOn 4 November 1964, Khomeini was secretly taken to [[Ankara]] and then to [[Bursa]], [[Turkey]]. On 5 September 1965, he moved to [[Najaf]], [[Iraq]] and stayed there until Saddam Hussein deported him. Finally, he was exiled by the pressure of [[Mohammad Reza Pahlavi]] to [[Neauphle-le-Ch\u00e2teau]], [[Paris]] on 6 October 1978.<ref name=\"Islam\">{{cite book |last1=Mutalib |first1=Hussin |title=Islam, Muslims and the Modern State: Case-Studies of Muslims in Thirteen Countries |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan (June 18, 1996) |isbn=978-0-333-66969-3}}</ref>\n\n==Political activity before exile==\n[[File:\u062e\u0645\u06cc\u0646\u06cc \u0648 \u0645\u0631\u062f\u0645.JPG|200 px|thumb|right|Khomeini with people]]\nIn 1944 Khomeini published his first book, ''[[Kashf al-Asrar]]'' (\u201cSecrets Unveiled\u201d), attacking secularisation under [[Reza Shah Pahlavi]] and advocating for the power of [[Allah]] to establish and disestablish governments.<ref>Vahdat, Farzin; ''God and Juggernaut: Iran's Intellectual Encounter With Modernity'', p. 182 {{ISBN|9780815629474}}</ref>\nAfter the death of Borujerdi in 1961, Khomeini became the leading ''Marja'''.<ref name=\"q\">{{cite book |last1=Fadaee |first1=Simin |title=Social Movements in Iran: Environmentalism and Civil Society (Iranian Studies) |publisher=Routledge; 1 edition (March 29, 2012) |isbn=978-0-415-69357-8 |page=55 |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Social_Movements_in_Iran.html?id=jsKKYuNky_0C}}</ref> \n\nIn January 1963, the Shah announced the [[White Revolution]], a six-point program of reform calling for land reform, nationalization of the forests, the sale of state-owned enterprises to private interests, electoral changes to enfranchise women and allow non-Muslims to hold office, profit-sharing in industry, and a literacy campaign in the nation's schools. On the other hand, he and many religious leaders considered the revolution had trends of westernizing the country and would in their mind threaten the traditional Islamic lifestyle of the common folk.<ref>[http://www.nmhschool.org/tthornton/mehistorydatabase/arabisraeliwars.htm#white%20revolution] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071224172550/http://www.nmhschool.org/tthornton/mehistorydatabase/arabisraeliwars.htm#white%20revolution |date=24 December 2007 }}</ref>\nThe Shah himself traveled to Qom and announced the clergy black reactionaries worse than the red reactionaries and a hundred times more treacherous than the (communist) tudeh party during his speech. On 26th January 1963, he held a referendum to get the appearance of public support in which 5.6 million against 4.1 people vote for the reformation. The referendum was a good excuse for the government to take tougher practical action against the clergy and on 22nd march 1963, coincides with the death-day of [[Ja'far al-Sadiq]], the Shah's guards attacked [[Feyziyeh School]]and kill students and people. <ref>{{cite book |last1=Singh;  Singh |first1=Manjit , D.P. |title=Violence: Impact and Intervention |publisher=Atlantic (2008) |isbn=978-8126909414 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=38SwtIHR11QC&pg=PA79&lpg=PA79&dq=SAVAK+attack+on+Feyziyeh+1963&source=bl&ots=SzVaSGZr6e&sig=ACfU3U3rVn4mdd-TKN0J02TBudnh9tua0w&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjNw47UzeHkAhXMJFAKHXPrA2kQ6AEwGXoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=SAVAK%20attack%20on%20Feyziyeh%201963&f=false}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Koya |first1=Abdar Rahman |title=Imam Khomeini: Life, Thought and Legacy |publisher=Islamic Book Trust (June 1, 2010) |isbn=978-9675062254 |page=32 |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Imam_Khomeini_Life_Thought_and_Legacy.html?id=HMd5C4KaOgkC}}</ref>According to Daniel Brumberg, the regime persuaded the thugs to attack the students of Feyziyeh School.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Brumberg |first1=Daniel |title=Reinventing Khomeini The Struggle for Reform in Iran |publisher=University Of Chicago Press (April 15, 2001) |isbn=978-0226077574 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aPT9QRtDMr8C&pg=PA74&lpg=PA74&dq=attack+to+feyziye#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> On the afternoon of [[Ashura]] (3 June 1963),  Khomeini presented a lecture at the Feyziyeh School<ref>{{cite book |last1=Sharifi Isaloo |first1=Amin |title=Power, Legitimacy and the Public Sphere: The Iranian Taziyeh Theatre Ritual |publisher=Taylor & Francis Group, 2018 |isbn=978-0-367-08541-4 |page=85 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LzbvugEACAAJ&dq=Power,+Legitimacy+and+the+Public+Sphere&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjXmZv5nNjdAhWGBiwKHZhmDeEQ6AEILDAB}}</ref> and inculpated the Shah as a \"wretched miserable man\", advised him to change his  ways, otherwise the day will come that people will be happy to see him leave, drawing parallels to the caliph Yazid, who is perceived as a 'tyrant' by [[Shia Islam|Shias]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iranchamber.com/history/rkhomeini/ayatollah_khomeini.php |title= Moin, Khomeini |year= 2000 |page= 104}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Nineteen Years on Departure of Islamic Republic Founder |url=https://www.english.alahednews.com.lb/essaydetails.php?eid=3948&cid=391#.W6yOdHszaM9}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 June 1963 at 3 am, two days after, Khomeini was detained and transferred to [[Tehran]]. When this news was broadcast, large protest demonstrations were held in Qom, Tehran, [[Mashhad]], [[Varamin]], [[Kashan]] and other cities. The Shah's guards killed and injured several people. That event is now referred to as the [[Movement of 15 Khordad]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hiro |first1=Dilip |title=Iran Under the Ayatollahs (Routledge Revivals) |publisher=Routledge; 1 edition (February 16, 2013) |isbn=978-0-415-66969-6 |page=47}}</ref> On 3 August, the Shah released Khomeini from jail and placed him under house arrest.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hiro |first1=Dilip |title=Iran Under the Ayatollahs (Routledge Revivals) |publisher=Routledge; 1 edition (February 16, 2013) |isbn=978-0-415-66969-6 |page=48|url=https://www.amazon.com/Iran-Under-Ayatollahs-Routledge-Revivals/dp/0415669693}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 October 1964, Khomeini condemned the Shah because of the [[diplomatic immunity]] he granted to [[American citizens]], civilian or military personnel in Iran.<ref name=\"q\" /> On 4 November 1964 Khomeini was arrested by [[SAVAK]]. He was then taken to Mehrabad international airport in Tehran and sent to Turkey.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hiro |first1=Dilip |title=Iran Under the Ayatollahs (Routledge Revivals) |publisher=Routledge; 1 edition (February 16, 2013) |isbn=978-0-415-66969-6 |page=49 |url=https://www.amazon.com/Iran-Under-Ayatollahs-Routledge-Revivals/dp/0415669693}}</ref>\n\n== Life in exile ==\n[[File:\u062e\u0645\u06cc\u0646\u06cc \u062f\u0631 \u062a\u0631\u06a9\u06cc\u0647.JPG|150 px|thumb|Khomeini in exile at [[Bursa]], Turkey without clerical dress]]\n\n=== Turkey ===\nA week after his arrival in Turkey, Khomeini was sent to [[Bursa]] and he stayed there for eleven months. He was hosted by a colonel in the Turkish Military intelligence named Ali Cetiner in his own residence.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sciolino |first=Elaine |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9E06E0D9153EF934A1575BC0A9669C8B63&sec=&pagewanted=all |title=nyt.com The People's Shah |work=The New York Times |date=27 August 2000 |accessdate=19 March 2010}}</ref> According to Turkish law, clerical dress was banned and Khomeini was never allowed to meet people. On 3 December 1964, his son, [[Mostafa Khomeini|Mostafa]], joined him.<ref name=\"w\">{{cite web |last1=Algar |first1=Dr. Hamid |title=Imam Khomeini: A Short Biography |url=https://www.al-islam.org/imam-khomeini-short-biography-dr-hamid-algar/years-struggle-and-exile-1962-1978 |publisher=The Institute for the Compilation and Publication of the Works of Imam Khomeini}}</ref> In his first days in Turkey, Khomeini was extremely angry at the secular dress of Turkish women, but he learned to adapt quickly to his new surroundings.<ref>Willett, Edward; ''Ayatollah Khomeini'', p. 48 {{ISBN|0823944654}}</ref> Despite the bans on contact with Khomeini, he and his students \u2013 most notably future [[President of Iran|President]] [[Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani]] \u2013 would plot the successful assassination of [[Prime Minister of Iran|Prime Minister]] [[Hassan-Ali Mansur]] as soon as Khomeini left Iran.<ref name=\"Evolution\"/>\n\nIn Bursa, Khomeini possessed a great deal of spare time, with the result that he continued his studies and for the first time moved away from the \u201ctraditional\u201d view of clerical involvement in politics.<ref>Rahimi, Babak; ''Contentious Legacies of the Ayatollah'', in Adib-Moghaddam, Arshin (editor); ''A Critical Introduction to Khomeini'', p. 296 {{ISBN|1107012678}}</ref> He wrote his second book, ''[[Tahrir al-Wasilah]]'', and began to receive huge donations from Iranian supporters who already opposed the Shah\u2019s policies.<ref name=\"Khomeini135137\">{{cite book |last1=Moin |first1=Baqer |title=Khomeini: Life of the Ayatollah |publisher=I.B. Tauris; Reprint edition (July 15, 2009) |isbn=978-1-84511-790-0 |pages=135-137}}</ref> The extent of donations to the Ayatollah caused the Shah and Turkish government to lift the ban on communication with his during the summer of 1965, and several clergy visited Khomeini \u2013 who was wearing secular garb \u2013 in Istanbul in 1965.<ref name=\"Khomeini135137\"/>\n\nOn September 5, 1965, Khomeini left Turkey and went to Najaf in Iraq.<ref name=\"e\">{{cite book |last1=Koya |first1=Abdar Rahman |title=Iman Khomeini: Life, Thought and Legacy |publisher=Islamic Book Trust (June 1, 2010) |isbn=978-9675062254 |page=36}}</ref>\n\nThe reasons for Khomeini's exile to Najaf by the Shah's regime are described as:<ref name=\"w\" />\n# The regime hoped to diminish the role of Khomeini through competition with Iraqi Ulama like [[Abu al-Qasim al-Khoei]]<ref>{{cite book |last1=Moin |first1=Baqer |title=Khomeini: Life of the Ayatollah |publisher=I.B. Tauris; Reprint edition (July 15, 2009) |isbn=978-1-84511-790-0 |pages=141}}</ref>\n# Because of intense pressure and popular protests.\n# Scholars and Khomeini's followers began to communicate with him in Bursa, donating so much money that the Ayatollah went from virtually penniless to very rich\n#  A [[SAVAK]] agent thought that his presence made the Turkish people hostile toward the Shah\u2019s regime.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Moin |first1=Baqer |title=Khomeini: Life of the Ayatollah |publisher=I.B. Tauris; Reprint edition (July 15, 2009) |isbn=978-1-84511-790-0 |page=138}}</ref>\n\n=== Iraq ===\n[[File:Rouhollah Khomeini in exile, Najaf, Pilgrimage the shrine of Imam Ali (3).jpg|150 px|thumb|Rouhollah Khomeini in exile, Najaf, Pilgrimage the shrine of Imam Ali]]\nOn 8 September 1965, Khomeini entered Iraq<ref name=\"e\" /> and would spend thirteen years there. Iraq did not have good political relations with the Shah.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Woods |first1=Kevin M. |title=Saddam's Generals: Perspectives of the Iran-Iraq War |publisher=Institute for Defense Analysis; 1st edition (October 28, 2011) |isbn=978-0-16-089613-2 |page=89 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=A6k9EFp_ijEC&q=Saddam%E2%80%99s+Generals:+Perspectives+of+the+Iran-Iraq+War&dq=Saddam%E2%80%99s+Generals:+Perspectives+of+the+Iran-Iraq+War&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjayYbxiuLdAhUpPewKHZu2DBEQ6AEIJjAA}}</ref>\n\nKhomeini and Mostafa entered Iraq. He went to [[Kadhimiya]] and stayed in the company of [[Mohammad al-Husayni al-Shirazi]] for two days before going to [[Karbala]]. From there he went to the city of Najaf.<ref name=\"r\">{{cite web |last1=Al-Awsat |first1=Asharq |title=Khomeini: From Ataturk Avenue to the Holy City of Najaf |url=https://eng-archive.aawsat.com/theaawsat/features/khomeini-from-ataturk-avenue-to-the-holy-city-of-najaf}}</ref> Initially, Khomeini was isolated by Iraq\u2019s Shi'a clergy because of his status as a foreigner and his radical teachings and support for [[Islamic terrorism|terrorism]]<ref name=\"Evolution\">Zahed, Mosa; ''The Evolution and Ascension of Iran\u2019s Terror Apparatus'', in Casaca, Paulo and Wolf, Siegfried O. (editors); ''Terrorism Revisited: Islamism, Political Violence and State-Sponsorship'', p. 67 {{ISBN|9783319556895}}</ref>; however, after a while [[ Muhammad Baqir al-Sadr ]] and other Iraqi clerics would join with Khomeini because they shared similar aims in establishing an Islamic state.<ref name=\"Evolution\"/> Khomeini would also be helped in his first days in Iraq by then-President [[Abdul Salam Arif]], who allowed the Ayatollah to set up and control an Iranian opposition radio station.<ref name=\"Evolution\"/>\n\nAfter a while, his wife [[Khadijeh Saqafi]] and second son [[Ahmad Khomeini]] joined them in Najaf.<ref name=\"r\" /> Khomeini began teaching [[Fiqh]] in the Sheikh Morteza Ansari Madrassah which captivated students mainly from Iran, Iraq, India, Pakistan, Afghanistan, and the Persian Gulf states.<ref name=\"y\">{{cite book |last1=Koya |first1=Abdar Rahman |title=Imam Khomeini: Life, Thought and Legacy |publisher=Islamic Book Trust (June 1, 2010) |isbn=978-9675062254 |page=37 |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Imam_Khomeini_Life_Thought_and_Legacy.html?id=HMd5C4KaOgkC}}</ref> On April 1967, Khomeini wrote the two letters, once to Ulama in order to persuade them to attempt to overthrow the Shah's regime and another to [[Amir-Abbas Hoveyda]], protesting the coronation of the Shah<ref>Dabashi, Hamid; ''Theology of Discontent: The Ideological Foundation of the Islamic Revolution'', p. ''lix'' {{ISBN|1412805163}}</ref> and condemning him for continued violation of both Islam and [[Constitution of Iran|the constitution]].<ref>Algar, Hamid; ''Roots of the Islamic Revolution in Iran'', {{ISBN|9780905081168}}</ref> Also, Khomeini forbade any type of dealing with Israel.<ref name=\"i\">{{cite book |last1=Koya |first1=Abdar Rahman |title=Imam Khomeini: Life, Thought and Legacy |publisher=Islamic Book Trust (June 1, 2010) |isbn=978-9675062254 |page=38}}</ref> Four years into his Iraqi exile, between 21 January and 8 February (1970), Khomeini gave lectures about [[Guardianship of the Islamic Jurist|Vilayat-e Faq\u012bh]] ya [[Islamic state|Hukumat-i Islami]], which in Shia Islam hold that Islam gives a ''faq\u012bh'' (Islamic jurist) custodianship over people.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">''[[Islam and Revolution]]'' (1981), pp. 29\u201330.</ref>\n\nThis became Khomeini\u2019s most famous and influential work, and laid out his ideas on governance (at that time):\n\n* That the laws of society should be made up only of the laws of God (''[[Sharia]]''), which cover \"all human affairs\" and \"provide instruction and establish norms\" for every \"topic\" in \"human life.\"<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n* Since ''Shariah'', or Islamic law, is the proper law, those holding government posts should have knowledge of ''Sharia.'' Since Islamic jurists or ''faq\u012bh'' have studied and are the most knowledgeable in ''Sharia'', the country's ruler should be a ''[[faq\u012bh]]'' who \"surpasses all others in knowledge\" of Islamic law and justice,<ref>''Islam and Revolution'' (1981), p. 59.</ref> (known as a [[Marja al-taqlid|marja']]), as well as having intelligence and administrative ability. Rule by monarchs and/or assemblies of \"those claiming to be representatives of the majority of the people\" (i.e. elected parliaments and legislatures) has been proclaimed \"wrong\" by Islam.<ref>''Islam and Revolution'', (1981), p. 31, 56</ref>\n* This system of clerical rule is necessary to prevent injustice, corruption, oppression by the powerful over the poor and weak, innovation and deviation of Islam and Sharia law; and also to destroy anti-Islamic influence and conspiracies by non-Muslim foreign powers.<ref>''Islam and Revolution'' (1981), p. 54.</ref> The theory in Shia Islam which holds that Islam gives a ''faq\u012bh'' (Islamic jurist) custodianship over people.\n\nTo formed an Islamic government, Two things were needed:<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hovsepian-Bearce |first1=Yvette Hovsepian-Bearce |title=The Political Ideology of Ayatollah Khamenei: Out of the Mouth of the Supreme Leader of Iran (UCLA Center for Middle East Development (CMED) series) |publisher=Routledge; 1 edition (May 20, 2017) |isbn=978-1-138-08655-5 |page=9}}</ref>\n# Overthrow of the Shah\n# Establishment of Shi'i theocracy\nKhomeini had mooted this theory as early as the middle 1940s in his first book ''Kashf al-Asrar''.<ref name=\"y\" />\n\nFrom 1971 to 1975, Khomeini demonstrated vehement opposition to the [[2,500 year celebration of the Persian Empire]], and the changing of the Iranian calendar from [[Islamic calendar|Hijri]] to Imperial (Shahanshahi).<ref name=\"i\" /> During this era, the Shah considered exiling Khomeini, now known as the \u201cImam\u201d, to [[India]], because he believed doing so would make communication between the Imam and his followers in Iran impossible,<ref name=\"i\" /> but for an unrevealed reason this plan was never executed. Khomeini was also faced with hostility from the [[Ba'athist Iraq|Ba'ath regime]], which began so hostile to his brand of Islam as the Shah.<ref>Bernhardt, Florian; \u2018Firm conviction or forced belief? The Islamic Da\u2018wah Party\u2019s response to Khomeini\u2019s theory of ''wilayat al-faqih''\u2019; ''International Journal of Contemporary Iraqi Studies'', Volume 6, Number 3, 1 September 2012, pp. 299-314</ref>\n\nIn November 1977, the Shah's overthrow began with the assassination of Khomeini's son, Mostafa, by SAVAK.<ref name=\"i\" /><ref name=\"y\" />\n\n[[File:Ruhollah Khomeini in Neauphle-le-Ch\u00e2teau (37).jpg|200 px|thumb|right|Imam Khomeini, in Neauphle-le-Ch\u00e2teau, Paris, France]]\n\n=== France ===\nOn September 24, 1978, according to a meeting held in [[New York City]] between Iraqi and Iranian foreign minister,<ref>Campo, Juan Eduardo; ''Encyclopedia of Islam'', p. 436 {{ISBN|0816077452}}</ref> Khomeini was forced by Iraqi strongman [[Saddam Hussein]] to leave Najaf, although the Shah and Hussein had begun plans to expel the Imam as early as 1975.<ref>Law, Diane; ''The Secret History of the Great Dictators: Saddam Hussein'' {{ISBN|1780333382}}</ref> The Ayatollah preferred to go to another Muslim country, and obtained [[travel visa|a visa]] for [[visa policy of Kuwait|Kuwait]],<ref name=\"Religious\">Mohammad Ayatollahi Tabaar; ''Religious Statecraft: The Politics of Islam in Iran'', p. 65 {{ISBN|0231183666}}</ref> but was turned back at the border because he had obtained the visa under the name \u201cRuhollah Mustafavi\u201d.<ref>Rajaee, Farhang; ''Islamism and Modernism: The Changing Discourse in Iran'', p. 113 {{ISBN|0292774362}}</ref> Khomeini\u2019s next preference was to go to [[Syria]] \u2013 where some sources say the Imam had intended to permanently reside even when he attempted to enter [[Kuwait]]<ref>Buchan James; ''Days of God: The Revolution in Iran and Its Consequences'', p. 177 {{ISBN|1416597778}}</ref> \u2013 but the lingering influence of [[Ahmed Hassan al-Bakr]] in Iraqi and Syrian politics meant that [[Syrian government]] would not accept him.<ref>Ganji, Babak; ''Politics of Confrontation: The Foreign Policy of the USA and Revolutionary Iran'', p. 39</ref> Khomeini then considered going to [[Bahrain]], [[India]], [[Pakistan]] or [[Algeria]],<ref name=\"Religious\"/> but his US-educated nationalist aide, [[Ebrahim Yazdi]], argued that Khomeini should move to the West because of the greater communication opportunities offered there, with Paris offering the best option for communication with the world of his revolutionary message.<ref> Mohammad Ayatollahi Tabaar; ''Religious Statecraft''. p. 66</ref>\n\nOn October 11, 1978, after Khomeini was moved to [[Neauphle-le-Ch\u00e2teau]] outside [[Paris]], France. From the advantages this decision was to keep faraway clerics and Ulama.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Chehabi |first1=H.E. |title=Iranian Politics and Religious Modernism: The Liberation Movement of Iran Under the Shah and Khomeini |publisher=Cornell University Press; 1 edition (January 1, 1990) |isbn=978-0-8014-2416-8 |page=242 |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Iranian_Politics_and_Religious_Modernism.html?id=JJEIQbUnGyYC}}</ref> Citiation in Frances such as some communication facilities and political atmosphere make more efficient relation with people in Iran. In France, because of journalists and the press, Khomeini's speeches were published rapidly in global media.<ref name=\"y\" /> Khomeini wanted to people that continued protests against the government.<ref>Moin, ''Khomeini'', (2000), p. 203</ref>  Between August and December 1978, strikes and demonstrations paralyzed Iran, so that the Shah left the country for exile on 16 January 1979, as the last Persian monarch, leaving his duties to a regency council and an opposition-based prime minister, [[Shapour Bakhtiar]].\n==Return from exile==\nOn Thursday, 1 February 1979, Ruhollah Khomeini was invited back to Iran by the government<ref name=\"Milani-Persians\"/><ref name=\"Milani Shah\"/> and returned to Iran.<ref name=\"i\" />\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Ideocracy]]\n* [[Ruhollah Khomeini]]\n* [[Ruhollah Khomeini's letter to Mikhail Gorbachev]]\n* [[Ruhollah Khomeini's residency (Jamaran)]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Iran|Politics|Shia Islam}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Khomeini, Ruhollah}}\n[[Category:Ruhollah Khomeini| ]]\n[[Category:Iranian emigrants to France]]\n[[Category:Iranian emigrants to Iraq]]\n[[Category:Iranian emigrants to Turkey]]\n", "name_user": "R'n'B", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toConstitution of Iran(link changed toPersian Constitution of 1906) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ruhollah_Khomeini%27s_life_in_exile"}
{"title_page": "The Bastard Sword", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Bastard Sword\n| image          = file:The_Bastard_Sword_Theatrical_Poster.jpg\n| caption        = Original theatrical release poster<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt7251886/mediaviewer/rm591471360. Internet Movie Datebase .]</ref>\n| director       = Eveshka Ghost\n| starring       = Xander Phillips, Martyn Eade, Seth Easterbrook\n| distributor    = Rusalka Pictures, Bayview Entertainment\n| released       = {{Film date|2018|12|09|df=y}}\n| runtime        = 181 minutes<ref>[https://bbfc.co.uk/releases/bastard-sword-film] British Board of Film Classification.]</ref>\n| language       = English\n}}\n'''''The Bastard Sword''''' is a 2018 medieval [[Fantasy film|fantasy]] [[Adventure film|adventure]] film written and directed by Eveshka Ghost. It stars Xander Phillips, Seth Easterbrook and Martyn Eade. The film tells the story of a magical sword that can control a man's thoughts.\n\nThe Bastard Sword had a modest theatrical opening and received mostly positive reviews and proved to be an example that an independent picture could still tell a story and look visually appealing even with a modest budget.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.filminquiry.com/bastard-sword-2018-reivew/|title=THE BASTARD SWORD: Inspiring For Micro-Budget Feature Filmmakers|last=Bedford|first=Tom|date=2019-01-11|website=Film Inquiry|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\n== Plot ==\nXander Phillips plays a fighter named Tias who finds himself lost in the forest looking to find The Bastard Sword for noble intentions but he is not alone. On his quest there is a thief named Mars who is also after the sword for his own selfish means. After Tias meets a mysterious hermit called Ulysses played by Seth Easterbrook, the three must form an unlikely alliance and work together to find the sword, but it can only be claimed by one.\n\nXander stated in an interview that \"The film takes a lot of influence from [[English mythology|English Mythology]] and [[Slavic folklore|Slavic Folklore]] and serves as a perfect medium to showcase a world that we wouldn't normally be familiar with\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mixcloud.com/MusicfromtheMovies/music-from-the-movies-26-april-2019-the-bastard-sword-movie-interview-show-84/?play=fb|title=Music from the Movies - 26 April 2019 - The Bastard Sword Movie Interview (Show 84)|last=Movies|first=Music from the|website=Mixcloud|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\n== Cast ==\n\n* Xander Phillips as Tias, A [[Fighter (Dungeons & Dragons)|fighter]] and main protagonist of the story.\n* Martyn Eade as Mars, A thief and main antagonist of the story.\n* Seth Easterbrook as Ulysses \n* Danielle Thorpe as Nyx\n* Chris Wilson as Viktor\n* James McClusky as Lars\n*Gemma Comber as Liliya\n*Chris Comber as Nikolai\n\n== Awards ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Year\n!Award\n!Category \n!Result\n!Reference\n|-\n|2018\n|Queen Palm International Film Festival\n|Best Score\n|Won\n|<ref>[https://www.queenpalmfilmfest.org/april-2019-main-category-gold]</ref>\n|-\n|2019\n|Los Angeles Film Awards\n|Best Score\n|Won\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lafilmawards.net/february-2019|title=February 2019|website=LA Film Awards|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n|-\n|2019\n|Global Film Awards\n|Best Indie FIlmmaker\n|Won\n|<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.gffawards.com/feb2019?lightbox=dataItem-jtr60xdy|title=GFF Awards Winners of Monthly Competitions|website=gffawards|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n|-\n|2019\n|Global Film Awards\n|Best Original Score\n|Won\n|<ref name=\":0\" />\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|7251886}}\n*[https://shotonwhat.com/the-bastard-sword-2018 The Bastard Sword] on [https://shotonwhat.com/ Shot on What?]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bastard Sword, The}}\n[[Category:British fantasy adventure films]]\n[[Category:2010s fantasy adventure films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British independent films]]\n[[Category:2018 films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Bastard Sword\n| image          = file:The_Bastard_Sword_Theatrical_Poster.jpg\n| caption        = Original theatrical release poster<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt7251886/mediaviewer/rm591471360. Internet Movie Datebase .]</ref>\n| director       = Eveshka Ghost\n| starring       = Xander Phillips, Martyn Eade, Seth Easterbrook\n| distributor    = Rusalka Pictures, Bayview Entertainment\n| released       = {{Film date|2018|12|09|df=y}}\n| runtime        = 181 minutes<ref>[https://bbfc.co.uk/releases/bastard-sword-film] British Board of Film Classification.]</ref>\n| language       = English\n}}\n'''''The Bastard Sword''''' is a 2018 medieval [[Fantasy film|fantasy]] [[Adventure film|adventure]] film written and directed by Eveshka Ghost. It stars Xander Phillips, Seth Easterbrook and Martyn Eade. The film tells the story of a magical sword that can control a man's thoughts.\n\nThe Bastard Sword had a modest theatrical opening and received mostly positive reviews and proved to be an example that an independent picture could still tell a story and look visually appealing even with a modest budget.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.filminquiry.com/bastard-sword-2018-reivew/|title=THE BASTARD SWORD: Inspiring For Micro-Budget Feature Filmmakers|last=Bedford|first=Tom|date=2019-01-11|website=Film Inquiry|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\n== Plot ==\nXander Phillips plays a fighter named Tias who finds himself lost in the forest looking to find The Bastard Sword for noble intentions but he is not alone. On his quest there is a thief named Mars who is also after the sword for his own selfish means. After Tias meets a mysterious hermit called Ulysses played by Seth Easterbrook, the three must form an unlikely alliance and work together to find the sword, but it can only be claimed by one.\n\nXander stated in an interview that \"The film takes a lot of influence from [[English mythology|English Mythology]] and [[Slavic folklore|Slavic Folklore]] and serves as a perfect medium to showcase a world that we wouldn't normally be familiar with\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mixcloud.com/MusicfromtheMovies/music-from-the-movies-26-april-2019-the-bastard-sword-movie-interview-show-84/?play=fb|title=Music from the Movies - 26 April 2019 - The Bastard Sword Movie Interview (Show 84)|last=Movies|first=Music from the|website=Mixcloud|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\n== Cast ==\n\n* Xander Phillips as Tias, A [[Fighter (Dungeons & Dragons)|fighter]] and main protagonist of the story.\n* Martyn Eade as Mars, A thief and main antagonist of the story.\n* Seth Easterbrook as Ulysses \n* Danielle Thorpe as Nyx\n* Chris Wilson as Viktor\n* James McClusky as Lars\n*Gemma Comber as Liliya\n*Chris Comber as Nikolai\n\n== Awards ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Year\n!Award\n!Category \n!Result\n!Reference\n|-\n|2018\n|Queen Palm International Film Festival\n|Best Score\n|Won\n|<ref>[https://www.queenpalmfilmfest.org/april-2019-main-category-gold]</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|7251886}}\n*[https://shotonwhat.com/the-bastard-sword-2018 The Bastard Sword] on [https://shotonwhat.com/ Shot on What?]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bastard Sword, The}}\n[[Category:British fantasy adventure films]]\n[[Category:2010s fantasy adventure films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British independent films]]\n[[Category:2018 films]]\n", "name_user": "JezMichaels", "label": "safe", "comment": "Citations added", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Bastard_Sword"}
